[It is correct to state that the experiments reported by Hill et al., did
not feature the BSE prion. This was neither implied nor stated in the
previous post. The experiments conducted by Professor Collinge's group
raise legitimate concerns about the transmission of prions between species.
In their paper, now published in PNAS, these workers report that a strain
of (scrapie-derived) hamster prions thought to be non-pathogenic for
conventional mice initiated prion replication to high levels in such mice
without producing clinical disease. Furthermore prions pathogenic in both
mice and hamsters were produced. Perhaps the most significant conclusion
from these experiments is that: "Current definitions of the species
barrier, which have been based on clinical end-points, need to be
fundamentally reassessed". The paper is now in print: Hill AF, Joiner S,
Linehan J, Desbruslais M, Lantos PL, Collinge J.
Species-barrier-independent prion replication in apparently resistant
species. Proc Natl Acad Sci 2000; 97(18): 10248-53.
<http://www.pnas.org/cgi/content/abstract/97/18/10248>. -Mod.CP
